    topicCode: "OG-MOD-03-TOP-03",
    contentMd: `# Cesarean Section

Cesarean delivery, surgical extraction of the fetus through a suprapubic incision, represents the most common operative procedure in obstetrics globally. Rising cesarean rates, particularly in India where institutional deliveries have increased through JSY, necessitate judicious indications to balance prevention of maternal and fetal morbidity against operative risks including infection, hemorrhage, and thromboembolism.

## Indications and Classification

Cesarean delivery indications are classified as absolute (placenta previa covering the cervical os, vasa previa, transverse lie), relative (failed augmentation of labor, prior classical cesarean, active herpes simplex with vaginal lesions), and disputed (breech presentation, multiple gestation, prior vaginal delivery after cesarean). The classification into elective (planned preoperatively) versus emergency (intrapartum complications) guides timing and preparation.

The primary indications in India include cephalopelvic disproportion and prolonged labor (40-50%), breech presentation (15-20%), placental complications (10-15%), and previous cesarean delivery (10-15%). The cesarean rate has increased from 10% in 2005 to 20-30% in 2015 among institutional deliveries in India, raising concerns regarding overutilization, particularly in private facilities.

## Surgical Technique and Complications

The lower segment cesarean section (LSCS), performing an incision in the lower uterine segment where myometrial contraction is minimal, has become the standard approach, facilitating trial of labor in subsequent pregnancies. The Classical cesarean section, utilizing a vertical incision in the fundus, is reserved for preterm delivery, placenta previa covering the lower segment, or prior classical scar.

Immediate complications include hemorrhage (average blood loss 500-1000 mL), infection, and anesthetic complications. Bladder injury occurs in 0.5-1% of cases, managed by primary repair. Delayed complications include adhesion formation predisposing to chronic pelvic pain, small bowel obstruction, and subsequent infertility. The risk of placental abnormalities (accreta, percreta) increases with each cesarean delivery, particularly with prior placenta previa.

Maternal mortality from cesarean delivery ranges from 1 in 2600 in developed nations to 1 in 1000 in low-resource settings, primarily from hemorrhage and infection. In India, PMSMA protocols emphasize antibiotic prophylaxis (first-generation cephalosporin at induction or skin incision), uterotonics for placental delivery, and ergot alkaloid administration to reduce postpartum hemorrhage.

🎓 **NMC Competency**: Appropriate cesarean delivery indications prevent maternal and perinatal morbidity; surgical technique and perioperative care minimize complications.

💡 **Clinical Pearl**: In India, the "Right to Primary VBAC" guidelines encourage vaginal delivery attempts in selected cases (spontaneous labor onset, no contraindications, facility equipped for emergency cesarean), as primary cesarean rates have escalated inappropriately.

⚡ **Classical Incisions**: The type of uterine incision (lower segment transverse, lower segment vertical, classical) should be documented, influencing recommendations for future pregnancies and delivery planning.

🏥 **PMSMA Standard**: Cesarean delivery facilities must maintain blood banking, anesthesia capability, and protocols for managing hemorrhage and infection complications.

{{IMAGE: Lower segment cesarean section technique with anatomical boundaries and placental delivery}}

**Ref: DC Dutta's Textbook of Obstetrics, 9th ed. Chapter 22: Cesarean Section.**`,
