    topicCode: "OG-MOD-03-TOP-04",
    contentMd: `# Instrumental Delivery

Instrumental delivery, assistance of spontaneous delivery through forceps or vacuum extraction, represents an important operative option when delay in second stage labor or fetal distress warrants expedited delivery but vaginal delivery is feasible. However, rising cesarean delivery rates have led to decline in instrumental delivery skills, particularly in India, necessitating training and careful patient selection.

## Forceps Delivery

Obstetrical forceps, designed with cephalic curve and pelvic curve to accommodate fetal head anatomy and maternal pelvic geometry, provide traction and rotation of the fetal head. Forceps application is classified as outlet (scalp visible at introitus without separation of labia, fetal head at or on perineum), mid-cavity (fetal head at station ≥+2 but not on perineum), and high (fetal head above +2 station—not recommended due to maternal and fetal morbidity).

Strict prerequisites for safe forceps application include complete cervical dilation, empty bladder, ruptured membranes, known presentation (OA, ROT, LOT), confirmed station ≥+2, and absence of cephalopelvic disproportion. The position must be confirmed by feel (sagittal suture and fontanelles palpated through soft tissues) before application. Traction should follow the pelvic curve; forces applied perpendicular to the head without undue rotation minimize trauma.

## Vacuum Extraction

The vacuum cup (soft silicone or rigid plastic) creates negative pressure within the cup, permitting traction for fetal descent. Vacuum delivery carries lower maternal morbidity than forceps but is associated with increased fetal cephalohematoma and subgaleal hemorrhage. The instrument is relatively contraindicated in suspected fetal bleeding disorders (alloimmunization, hemophilia) and breech presentation.

Complications from instrumental delivery include maternal perineal trauma (3rd/4th degree tears), anal sphincter injury predisposing to fecal incontinence, and vaginal lacerations. Fetal complications include caput succedaneum (edema of scalp), cephalohematoma (bleeding beneath periosteum), retinal hemorrhages, intracranial hemorrhage (rare if application strictly adheres to prerequisites), and facial nerve injuries.

## Clinical Decision-Making

The decision for instrumental delivery requires objective evidence of delay: prolonged second stage (≥2 hours in nulliparous women with epidural, ≥3 hours without epidural; ≥1 hour in parous women with epidural, ≥2 hours without). Fetal distress documented by cardiotocography with pathological features also justifies intervention. Trial instrumental delivery is permissible in selected cases under specified conditions, with readiness for cesarean delivery if unsuccessful.

🎓 **NMC Competency**: Appropriate selection and skilled application of instrumental delivery, when prerequisites are met, prevent unnecessary cesarean delivery while ensuring maternal and fetal safety.

💡 **Clinical Pearl**: In India, with constrained obstetrical workforce in rural areas, training programs in safe instrumental delivery improve maternal outcomes by reducing reliance on cesarean delivery for second-stage delay.

⚡ **Prerequisites Checklist**: Confirmation of complete dilation, empty bladder, ruptured membranes, known presentation, and station ≥+2 must precede any instrumental application.

🏥 **JSY Training**: Training midwives and nurses in supervised forceps/vacuum delivery under appropriate clinical scenarios reduces maternal morbidity and cesarean delivery rates in institutional settings.

{{IMAGE: Forceps application and pelvic curve traction with correct and incorrect techniques}}

**Ref: DC Dutta's Textbook of Obstetrics, 9th ed. Chapter 23: Instrumental Delivery.**`,
