    topicCode: "OG-MOD-04-TOP-01",
    contentMd: `# Normal Puerperium

The puerperium, extending from delivery of the placenta until involution of the reproductive organs is complete (approximately 6 weeks), encompasses profound physiological and psychological changes. Systematic assessment during the postpartum period identifies complications and ensures optimal maternal recovery and lactation establishment. In the Indian context, where many women deliver in institutional settings under JSY, postpartum care protocols enhance outcomes.

## Physiological Changes

The uterus undergoes rapid involution, decreasing from 1000 g at delivery to 100 g at 6 weeks. The fundus descends approximately one fingerbreadth daily; by day 14, it becomes impalpable. Lochia—the normal postpartum vaginal discharge—progressively changes from rubra (dark red, containing blood and tissue) lasting 3-4 days, to serosa (watery, serous fluid) for 1-2 weeks, to alba (white, containing leukocytes and epithelial cells) lasting until day 21-28.

The cervix undergoes repair and remodeling; the external os remains dilated to 2-3 mm postpartum, gradually closing over subsequent weeks. Episiotomy wounds heal primarily within 7-10 days if appropriate care is maintained. The vaginal epithelium undergoes regression from gravid state; rugae reappear by 3 weeks. The abdominal wall musculature gradually regains tone; diastasis recti (separation of rectus muscles) typically resolves by 6-8 weeks postpartum.

Cardiovascular changes reverse progressively: plasma volume contracts toward prepregnancy values, blood viscosity increases as red cell mass remains expanded temporarily, and cardiac output decreases. The hemoglobin typically reaches prepregnancy levels by 4-6 weeks postpartum. Renal changes similarly normalize, with GFR returning to baseline and serum creatinine rising from pregnant levels.

## Lactation and Breastfeeding

Lactogenesis occurs in stages: Stage 1 (during pregnancy, mammary development and colostrum secretion), Stage 2 (lactogenesis proper, occurring 24-48 hours after placental delivery when milk composition transitions from colostrum to mature milk), and Stage 3 (milk maintenance through repeated emptying). Oxytocin, released during nipple stimulation, mediates the milk ejection reflex. Prolactin suppression by dopamine maintains lactational capacity.

Exclusive breastfeeding is recommended for the first 6 months, providing optimal nutrition and immune protection. Lactational amenorrhea provides unreliable contraception but represents a physiological benefit in the first 6 months if exclusive breastfeeding is maintained. Common complications include engorgement (treated with frequent feeding, cold compresses, and NSAIDs), mastitis (infection requiring antibiotics safe in lactation), and cracked/bleeding nipples (managed with correct latch and topical treatments).

🎓 **NMC Competency**: Systematic postpartum assessment and lactation support facilitate uncomplicated recovery and establish exclusive breastfeeding as recommended under national health policies.

💡 **Clinical Pearl**: In India, the "Integrated Management of Neonatal and Childhood Illness" (IMNCI) emphasizes immediate skin-to-skin contact and early initiation of breastfeeding within the first hour of delivery.

⚡ **Perineal Care**: Episiotomy wounds should be assessed daily for signs of infection; ice application within 24 hours reduces pain and swelling.

🏥 **Postpartum Counseling**: All women should receive counseling on warning signs (fever, foul-smelling lochia, excessive bleeding, severe pain) that warrant hospital return.

{{IMAGE: Fundal height regression and lochia color progression across postpartum weeks}}

**Ref: DC Dutta's Textbook of Obstetrics, 9th ed. Chapter 25: Puerperium and Lactation.**`,
